---- MODULE MCDieHarder --------------------------------------- *)     (**************************************************************************)    CONSTANTS Goal     == ... \* The set goal amount. Jug, Capacity := DieHarder(* We use the constants from module dieharderextended as our domain of discourse and extend it to include additional elements for TLC configuration.)
          MCJug     == {0} U [1..Goal]   (* A jug can be any integer between  *)    CONSTANTS MCCapacity(j) ==  IF j = 42 THEN Goal ELSE -3(* The capacity of the glass depends on what is in it. If a certain amount, say $50 (represented by number "Goal"), fits into jug then its full volume should be returned otherwise negative value to indicate that this configuration doesn't make sense.)
    INVARIANTS TypeOK  (\* The type invariant ensures the domain of discourse *)   (* is correct. In our case, it makes sure we are not using an integer outside       )     (of set {0} U [1..Goal] for jugs and all values in this range or less than zero)
                NotSolved(\* This invariant ensures that the goal amount can't *)   (* be reached by pouring water from one glass to another. In our case,  )     (it doesn’n make sense when Goals are more then jugs capacity and it should not    *be less than zero)
Spec == [](NotSolved /\ \E m :: {0} U [\Goal] : MCCapacity(m))(* We define the specification. It is a formula that describes what we want to prove: *) (* That there exists at least one pouring sequence from jugs with capacities in set of 1,2,... Goals*)    (\* such as (0), where each step i = m :: {j} means glass j has volume "m" after the operation. The formula says that we can reach a goal state by using at least one pouring sequence from jugs with capacities in set of 1,2,... Goal.)
=============================================================================     (**************************************************************************)    TLC Configuration: CONSTANTS Jug      == MCJug      (* We tell the tool to substitute *)   ((* our constant for a domain element. In this case it is an integer from {0} U [1..Goal])  )
          Capacity == MCCapacity(* And do so again with another one of     *)(*(We use function-valued expression here because TLC doesn't allow to write *)   ((* such in a configuration file. We tell it that we want the value from*)    (* our module extended by us for this constant)))
          Goal     == ...(* The goal amount is defined as per usual but  *)(*(it should be positive integer) ) SPECIFICATION Spec INVARIANTS TypeOK NotSolved This configuration tells TLC to use the constants and specification from our module, while substituting some of them with function-valued expressions. This allows us not only define a domain for Jug but also set its capacity using an auxiliary constant MCCapacity that depends on jug size (and possibly other parameters).
====